(42, 14, 15, 40, 25, 10, 10, 'Blessed is he that shall eat bread', 'Blessedness in the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of readiness and participation in the kingdom of God. Both passages emphasize the importance of being prepared to enter into a blessed state, whether it be eating bread in the kingdom or entering the marriage feast.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 15, 43, 6, 27, 59, 'Blessed is he that shall eat bread', 'Bread and Eternal Life', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of bread as a symbol of spiritual sustenance. In Luke, the blessedness of eating bread in God''s kingdom connects to Jesus'' declaration in John that he is the ''bread of life'' which grants eternal life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 15, 40, 8, 11, 11, 'Blessed is he that shall eat bread in the kingdom of God.', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of fellowship in the kingdom of God. Both passages emphasize the idea of sitting down with patriarchs in the kingdom, indicating a shared experience of blessing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 16, 40, 22, 2, 14, 'made a great supper', 'Invitation to a Feast', 'Both passages emphasize a great invitation to a meal, highlighting the rejection of those initially invited and the subsequent call to others. This connection highlights the theme of inclusion and the consequences of ignoring the invitation.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 16, 66, 22, 17, 17, 'a great supper, and bade many', 'Invitation to the Feast', 'This connection highlights the theme of invitation in both passages. In Luke 14:16, a man invites many to a great supper, while Revelation 22:17 invites all who are thirsty to come and take the water of life freely.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 16, 23, 25, 6, 7, 'great supper', 'Feast Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a great feast prepared by God for many people. The ''great supper'' in Luke parallels the ''feast of fat things'' in Isaiah, highlighting God''s invitation to all. This connection illustrates the abundant provision and celebration in God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 16, 23, 55, 1, 7, 'a great supper', 'Invitation to Abundant Provision', 'Both passages emphasize an invitation to partake in a feast or sustenance without cost. The ''great supper'' in Luke parallels the call to ''come ye to the waters'' in Isaiah, highlighting God''s provision for those in need.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 14, 16, 42, 14, 16, 24, 'A certain man made a great supper', 'Invitation to the Supper', 'Both passages emphasize the invitation to a great supper and the responses of those invited. The SOURCE verse introduces the supper, while the TARGET passage elaborates on the excuses made by the invited guests and the subsequent invitation to others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
